{
    "level": "sentence",
    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "A precise new KLOE measurement of |F \u03c0 | 2 with ISR events and determination of \u03c0\u03c0 contribution to a \u00b5 for 0.592 < M \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.975 GeV G. Venanzoni for the KLOE Collaboration 1",
            "paragraph_rank": 0,
            "section_rank": 1
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "INTRODUCTION",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "'The anomalous magnetic moment of the muon has recently been measured to an accuracy of 0.54 ppm [1]. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 97,
                    "end": 100,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "text": "[1]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The main source of uncertainty in the value predicted [2] in the Standard Model is given by the hadronic contribution, a hlo \u00b5 , to the lowest order. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 54,
                    "end": 57,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "[2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 121,
                    "end": 124,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "text": "hlo"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "This quantity is estimated with a dispersion integral of the hadronic cross section measurements.",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In particular, the pion form factor, F \u03c0 , defined via \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 \u2261 \u03c3 e + e \u2212 \u2192\u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 = \u03c0\u03b1 2 3s \u03b2 3 \u03c0 (s)|F \u03c0 (s)| 2 , accounts for \u223c 70% of the central value and for \u223c 60% of the uncertainty in a hlo \u00b5 . ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 192,
                    "end": 195,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "text": "hlo"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The KLOE experiment already published [3] a measurement of |F \u03c0 | 2 with the method described below, using an integrated luminosity of 140 pb \u22121 , taken in 2001, henceforth referred to as KLOE05, with a fractional systematic error of 1.3%.",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 38,
                    "end": 41,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b3",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "MEASUREMENT OF \u03c3 (e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3) AT DA\u03a6NE DA\u03a6NE is an e + e \u2212 collider running at \u221a s \u2243 M \u03c6 , the \u03c6 meson mass, which has provided an integrated luminosity of about 2.5 fb \u22121 to the KLOE experiment up to year 2006. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 42,
                    "end": 47,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "DA\u00ce\u00a6NE",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 48,
                    "end": 54,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "DA\u00ce\u00a6NE",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In addition, about 250 pb \u22121 of data have been collected at \u221a s \u2243 1 GeV, in 2006. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Present results are based on 240 pb \u22121 of data taken in 2002 (3.1 Million events) [4]. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 82,
                    "end": 85,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b4",
                    "text": "[4]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The KLOE detector consists of a drift chamber [5] with excellent momentum resolution (\u03c3 p /p \u223c 0.4% for tracks with polar angle larger than 45 \u2022 ) and an electromagnetic calorimeter [6] with good energy (\u03c3 E /E \u223c 5.7%/ E [GeV]) and precise time (\u03c3 t \u223c 54 ps/ E [GeV] \u2295 100 ps) resolution.",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 46,
                    "end": 49,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b5",
                    "text": "[5]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 182,
                    "end": 185,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b6",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "At DA\u03a6NE, we measure the differential spectrum of the \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 invariant mass, M \u03c0\u03c0 , from Initial State Radiation (ISR) events, e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3, and extract the total cross section \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 \u2261 \u03c3 e + e \u2212 \u2192\u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 using the following formula [7]:",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 239,
                    "end": 242,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b7",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ],
            "entity_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 3,
                    "end": 8,
                    "type": "software",
                    "rawForm": "DA\u00ce\u00a6NE",
                    "resp": "service",
                    "id": "software-simple-s3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "where H is the radiator function. ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "This formula neglects Final State Radiation (FSR) terms (which are properly taken into account in the analysis). ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In the small angle analysis, photons are emitted within a cone of \u03b8 \u03b3 < 15 \u2022 around the beam line (narrow blue cones in Fig. 1 left). ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 120,
                    "end": 132,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1 left)"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The two charged pion tracks have 50 \u2022 < \u03b8 \u03c0 < 130 \u2022 . ",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The photon is not explicitly detected and its direction is reconstructed by closing the kinematics:",
            "section": "INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "S.C. COIL",
            "section_rank": 3
        },
        {
            "text": "Cryostat",
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "The separation of pion and photon selection regions greatly reduces the contamination from the resonant process e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c6 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03c0 0 , in which the \u03c0 0 mimics the missing momentum of the photon(s) and from the final state radiation process e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 FSR . ",
            "section": "Cryostat",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "Since ISR-photons are mostly collinear with the beam line, a high statistics for the ISR signal events remains. ",
            "section": "Cryostat",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "On the other hand, a highly energetic photon emitted at small angle forces the pions also to be at small angles (and thus outside the selection cuts), resulting in a kinematical suppression of events with M 2 \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.35 GeV 2 . ",
            "section": "Cryostat",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 207,
                    "end": 208,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Residual contamination from the processes \u03c6 \u2192 \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03c0 0 and e + e \u2212 \u2192 \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 \u03b3 are rejected by cuts in the kinematical variable track-mass, 2 see Fig. 1 right. ",
            "section": "Cryostat",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 149,
                    "end": 155,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_0",
                    "text": "Fig. 1"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "A particle ID estimator, based on calorimeter information and time-of-flight, is used to suppress the high rate of radiative Bhabhas.",
            "section": "Cryostat",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 4
        },
        {
            "text": "EVALUATION OF",
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The \u03c0\u03c0\u03b3 differential cross section is obtained from the observed spectrum, N obs , after subtracting the residual background events, N bkg , and correcting for the selection efficiency, \u03b5 sel (M 2 \u03c0\u03c0 ), and the luminosity, L :",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "In order to correct for resolution effects, the differential cross section is unfolded using the Bayesian method described in [8]. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 129,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b8",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The integrated luminosity, L , is obtained [9] from the observed number of Bhabha events, divided by the effective cross section evaluated from the Monte Carlo generator Babayaga@NLO [10,11]. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 43,
                    "end": 46,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b9",
                    "text": "[9]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 183,
                    "end": 187,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b10",
                    "text": "[10,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 187,
                    "end": 190,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b11",
                    "text": "11]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The cross section \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 (M 0 \u03c0\u03c0 ) is obtained by accounting for final state emission (which shifts M \u03c0\u03c0 to the virtual photon mass M 0 \u03c0\u03c0 ) and dividing the \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 cross section by the radiator function H (obtained from Phokhara [12,13,14,15,16] by setting pion form factor F \u03c0 = 1) as in Eq. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 231,
                    "end": 235,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b12",
                    "text": "[12,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 235,
                    "end": 238,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "13,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 238,
                    "end": 241,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "14,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 241,
                    "end": 244,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "15,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 244,
                    "end": 247,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "16]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "1.",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "The bare cross section \u03c3 0 \u03c0\u03c0 , inclusive of FSR, needed for the a \u03c0\u03c0 \u00b5 dispersion integral, is obtained after removing vacuum polarization, VP, effects [17]. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 153,
                    "end": 157,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "[17]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Tab. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "1 left shows the list of fractional systematic uncertainties of a \u03c0\u03c0 \u00b5 in the mass range 0.35 < M 2 \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.95 GeV 2 .",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 9,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 114,
                    "end": 115,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b2",
                    "text": "2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Tab. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "1 right shows the good agreement amongst KLOE results, and also with the published CMD-2 and SND values. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "They all agree within one standard deviation.   ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 2 left shows a comparison of |F \u03c0 | 2 (obtained by \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 after subtraction of FSR (assuming pointlike pions) between CMD-2 [19], SND [20] and KLOE (with only statistical errors). ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 6,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 127,
                    "end": 131,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "[19]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 137,
                    "end": 141,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b20",
                    "text": "[20]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "For the energy scan experiments, whenever there are several data points falling in one 0.01 GeV 2 bin, we average the values. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "Fig. 2 right shows the absolute difference the a \u03c0\u03c0 \u00b5 values for each energy bin obtained in this analysis and the energy scan experiments. ",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 6,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "ref_id": "fig_1",
                    "text": "Fig. 2"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "All the experiments are in rather good agreement within errors.",
            "section": "EVALUATION OF",
            "paragraph_rank": 10,
            "section_rank": 5
        },
        {
            "text": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "KLOE has measured the dipion contribution to the muon anomaly, a \u03c0\u03c0 \u00b5 , in the interval 0.592 < M \u03c0\u03c0 < 0.975 GeV, with negligible statistical error and a 0.6% experimental systematic uncertainty. ",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Theoretical uncertainties in the estimate of radiative corrections increase the systematic error to 0.9%. ",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "Combining all errors KLOE gives:",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 11,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "This result represents an improvement of 30% on the systematic error with respect to the previous published value from KLOE. ",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "The new result confirms the current disagreement between the standard model prediction for a \u00b5 and the measured value, as shown in Fig. 3.",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 12,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 131,
                    "end": 137,
                    "type": "figure",
                    "text": "Fig. 3"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Independent analyses are in progress to:",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 13,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 extract the pion form factor from data taken at \u221a s = 1 GeV, off the \u03c6 resonance, where \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03c0 0 background is negligible, by using detected photons emitted at large angle. ",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "This analysis, which is very close to be finalized, allows to measure \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0 down to the 2-pion threshold; Comparison of a \u00b5 from theory and experiment. ",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 6
        },
        {
            "text": "KLOE08 is included in JEG08 [21] \u2022 measure the pion form factor directly from the ratio, bin-by-bin, of \u03c0 + \u03c0 \u2212 \u03b3 to \u00b5 + \u00b5 \u2212 \u03b3 spectra [22];",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 14,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 28,
                    "end": 32,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b21",
                    "text": "[21]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 135,
                    "end": 139,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b22",
                    "text": "[22]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "\u2022 measure \u03c3 \u03c0\u03c0(\u03b3) using the large angle analysis at the \u03c6 peak, which would improve the knowledge of the FSR interference effects (in particular the f 0 (980) contribution [23,24]).",
            "section": "CONCLUSIONS AND OUTLOOK",
            "paragraph_rank": 15,
            "section_rank": 6,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 172,
                    "end": 176,
